#: ../en/docs/related-documents.md:75
msgid "## How Does It Work?"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/related-documents.md:77
msgid "The way Qgoda computes the degree of relatedness between documents --- their \"relation score\" --- is completely transparent and easy to understand.  Try `qgoda config` and see the default configuration for the computation:"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/related-documents.md:79
msgid ""
"```yaml\n"
"$ qgoda config\n"
"...\n"
"link_score: 5\n"
"...\n"
"taxonomies:\n"
"  categories: 3\n"
"  links: 1\n"
"  tags: 2\n"
"...\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/related-documents.md:91
msgid "Let's take two documents A and B as an example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/related-documents.md:93
msgid ""
"```yaml\n"
"---\n"
"title: A\n"
"categories: hardware\n"
"tags: [Hard-disk, Storage, SATA, USB]\n"
"---"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/related-documents.md:100 ../en/docs/related-documents.md:114
msgid "See [B](/b/) for more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/related-documents.md:102 ../en/docs/related-documents.md:116
msgid "This site is generated with [Qgoda](http://www.qgoda.net).\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/related-documents.md:105
msgid "B looks like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/related-documents.md:107
msgid ""
"```yaml\n"
"---\n"
"title: B\n"
"categories: software\n"
"tags: [USB, Storage, Accessories]\n"
"---"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/related-documents.md:119
msgid "As you can see, document A links to document B.  The configured `C:link_score` is 5, and hence the relation score between them is 5.  Note: If B would link back to A, that would add another 5 points.  But subsequent mutual links would be ignored."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/related-documents.md:121
msgid "Both documents link to http://www.qgoda.net/.  Since the configuration variable `taxonomies.links` has the value 1, the score is now 6."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/related-documents.md:123
msgid "A is from category \"hardware\", B from \"software\".  That doesn't match and the 3 points from `taxonomies.categories` are *not* added."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/related-documents.md:125
msgid "But the two documents share the common tags \"USB\" and \"Storage\" counting 2 points (`taxonomies.tags`) each, so that the final relation score between the two documents is 10."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/related-documents.md:127
msgid "You can fine-tune the algorithm by changing the relevant configuration variables or by adding more taxonomies.  Set the score to 0 if you want to ignore a built-in taxonomy."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/related-documents.md:129
msgid "For example, if you want to enforce a relationship between two documents, configure this in `P:_config.yaml`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/related-documents.md:131
msgid ""
"```yaml\n"
"taxonomies:\n"
"  boost: 9999\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/related-documents.md:136
msgid "In your document `T:front-matter` put:"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/related-documents.md:138
msgid ""
"```yaml\n"
"---\n"
"...\n"
"boost: abcxyz\n"
"...\n"
"---\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/related-documents.md:146
msgid "Now all documents that have the property `boost` set to the same value (for example `abcxyz`) would be related.  Just pick another value than `abcxyz` for more relationships."
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/related-documents.md:148
msgid "### Displaying the Relation Score"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/related-documents.md:150
msgid "Why would you do that? Well, for debugging, maybe?  Okay, here you go:"
msgstr ""

#: ../en/docs/related-documents.md:152
msgid ""
